TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18
Imagine China / Reuters
China’s TikTok social network censored videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence or a banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
The documents found at the publication, it is said that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance company) with the help of the application promotes the goals of the foreign policy of China abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policy fall under the “incitement of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in a context appropriate to the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of the socialist system of China falls under the general ban “criticism or attacks on the politics and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.”.
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under the “distortion of the history of China or other countries.”
The document also gives a list of the banned names of the twenty "foreign leaders or government officials" of Nakhor Udai, including the North Korean leaders Kim Jong-Ira, Kim Il-Sen and Kim Jong-un, the Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, the American presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Yapon.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may result in the user being blocked.
Not too severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules have become obsolete and no longer apply: "We are now using a localized approach to moderation, as well as attracting independent local specialists."
Russian TikTok users have no specific restrictions on publication, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the Production Center.
“Production Center” is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Production Center" agrees with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without consent, reports Bogdanov.
When asked whether it is possible to speak about politics or Putin in TikTok, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, founder of Our Didgital, agrees with Bogdanov: “The basic rules for users of TikTok are listed in the user agreement: you should not post shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on.”
But these rules can include any content that moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
By user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over the age of 13.
Social network administrators check their age with artificial intelligence: the neuronet analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neuronet decides that the user is younger, his account can be removed, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork.
