“Sanctions” deliveries to Russia fell by 100 times
The Russian government has estimated that the supply of agricultural products and food to Russia from countries that have fallen under the Russian food embargo has decreased by more than 100 times since 2013.
According to a report sent to Russian President Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31 thousand tons of products were imported from sanctioned countries, compared to 3 million 442.2 thousand tons for the same period of 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time, the value of imported products decreased to $226.5 million from $4 billion 975.5 million respectively.
We are talking about the supply of goods that did not fall under the embargo.
As indicated in the report, the dropped volumes of prohibited products were compensated by the increase in imports from CIS countries, Africa, South-East Asia, Serbia.
At the end of August, the government extended until December 31, 2020, the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited for import into Russia under counter-sanctions.
In a document posted on the official legal information portal, it was noted that the validity of the rules was extended by another one per year - from December 31, 2019 to December 31, 2020.
Initially, the decree on the abolition of the sanctions applied to products from the United States, the EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, since August 13, 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein, and Ukraine have "joined" this list since January 1, 2016.
Putin’s decree on the destruction of illegally imported “sanctions” (products subject to a food embargo, which Moscow imposed in response to the anti-Russian sanctions of the West) entered into force in 2015.
In turn, the government authorized the destruction of “sanctioned” food in any legal way.
As Western sanctions continue, Russia has also extended its retaliatory measures.
At the same time, the measure does not apply to products that citizens import for personal use.
The prohibition does not apply to the import of goods for personal consumption weighing up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Council under the President of the Russian Federation on the development of civil society and human rights Mikhail Fedotov previously called "simplely immoral" the destruction of food, and this, according to him, has a negative impact on the education of people.
Moreover, with the initiative to ban the destruction of food suitable for consumption, in early June, Rospotrebnadzor spoke.
A similar recommendation was made to the government by the Human Rights Council under the President of the Russian Federation.
And Russian Deputy Prime Minister Alexey Gordeev said that destroying food is wrong, and you need to think about how you can use them for the purpose, assessing the quality.
