In Chile, began to build a telescope worth 1 billion euros
This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ESO).
This week, the construction of the dome of the European Extremely Large Telescope (E-ELT), the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomical project, has officially begun.
Its total cost, according to ESO estimates, will exceed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 billion.
Most of this money will be spent on equipment and the construction of the observatory building.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record large mirror, whose diameter will be about 39 meters.
It will be assembled from 798 hexagonal segments measuring 1.4 meters.
This huge mirror, as well as two auxiliary reflective surfaces with a diameter of 4.2 and 3.75 meters, will help the E-ELT get the first detailed pictures of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and also look for Earth's twins.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the surroundings of Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole in the center of the Milky Way.
Despite the fact that the construction of the dome has only just begun, scientists, engineers and other specialists have been developing mirrors, scientific tools and other components of the observatory for three years - since the announcement of the first plans for the construction of the E-ELT.
The contract for the production of the main mirror, which totalled about 400 million euros, was awarded to the German firm SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
